{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491161","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491161"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:35:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:35:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"850"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"850","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/850"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.31,0.32,0.02,0.12,0.23]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"850"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116293"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"850","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/850"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"850"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98289"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"350"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"119"},{"type":"contributions","id":"308"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17762"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32370"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49830"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116293","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116293"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-old-man is admitted to the emergency department of a tertiary referral hospital with a 12 hour history of rectal bleeding. He describes the passage of large amounts of dark red blood, filling the toilet bowl with clots. He is normally in good health, but two weeks ago developed back pain, for which he has been taking indomethacin. He is pale, with a blood pressure of 90/60 mmHg and a pulse of 120/min. Abdominal examination is unremarkable and on digital rectal inspection there is a large amount of maroon-coloured blood and clots. An intravenous infusion is started and his blood pressure one hour after admission is 110/70 mmHg and pulse 100/min. His haemoglobin is 80 g/L (130-180). He then passes more blood per rectum.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Colonoscopy","Upper GI tract endoscopy","Red cell scan","Sigmoidoscopy","CT angiography"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn any presentation of acute rectal blood loss it is important to consider the possibility that the bleed may be originating from the upper digestive tract. This likelihood is increased where there is haemodynamic instability and minimally altered blood is clearly visible in what is being passed per rectum. In some 15-20% of cases of haematochezia, the source of the bleeding is an upper gastrointestinal bleed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe term \u0027maroon-coloured blood\u0027 implies that there has been some alteration to the blood as it has passed down the digestive tract and it has not originated from the distal colon. This change in appearance of the blood suggests that the source of the blood loss is either from the proximal colon or the small intestine. Bleeding from a duodenal ulcer is not always associated with haematemesis. This site of bleeding is more likely to be the case when there is evidence of haemodynamic instability and the presence of risk factors (such as NSAID use) - both of which are suggested in this case. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe current guidelines suggest that the most appropriate plan of management in an haemodynamically unstable patient is to try and identify the site of bleeding with \u003Cstrong\u003ECT angiography\u003C/strong\u003E. However, this patient has responded to intravenous volume replacement and has a normal blood pressure. It is therefore makes sense to exclude an upper gastrointestinal source by performing an \u003Cstrong\u003Eupper tract endoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E. He has a risk factor for peptic ulcer disease (NSAIDs) so an upper GIT bleed must be considered.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOnce an endoscopy has been done and an upper gut cause excluded, the focus can be on the lower digestive tract. Although \u003Cstrong\u003Ecolonoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E would be ideal, it requires the patient to be haemodynamically stable and for the colon to be prepared and clear of significant ongoing bleeding. Likewise, a \u003Cstrong\u003Esigmoidoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E will be of limited value with a colon full of blood.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhen bleeding is ongoing as in the case above, it makes more sense to proceed - after endoscopy has excluded a remedial source in the stomach or duodenum - to CT angiography and if a bleeding source can be identified, embolisation can be considered.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A potential upper source of bleeding from the upper digestive tract must always be considered in any case of lower gastrointestinal bleeding."],"references":["Strate, LL, Gralnek, IM. ACG Clinical Guideline: Management of Patients with Acute Lower Gastrointestinal Bleeding. Am J Gastroenterol. 2016. 111:459\u2013474","Oakland K, Chadwick G, East JE, et al. Diagnosis and management of acute lower  gastrointestinal bleeding: guidelines from the British  Society of Gastroenterology. Gut 2019; 68:776\u201389.","Imran H, Alexander JT, Jackson CD. Lower Gastrointestinal Hemorrhage. JAMA. 2024; 331:1666-667.","Kate V, Sureshkumar S, Gurushankari B, et al. Acute Upper Non\u2010variceal and Lower Gastrointestinal Bleeding. J Gastrointest Surg 2022; 26:932\u201349."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98289"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"850"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98289","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98289"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-28T10:15:51+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T10:16:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"850"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116293"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"350","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/350"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","na